Compile instructions:
To compile manually, run: g++ -Wall -Wextra -std=c++11 -o simarm main.cpp
or, use Makefile:
    - In terminal, cd to directory containing Makefile, in this case, a3: cd ~/a3
    - To clean Makefile, run: make clean
    - To run Makefile, run: make

Operating instructions:
Ensure you are in the directory containing all of your files, in this case, a3
- To run program, run: ./simarm <sequence_length>

List/description of novel/significant design decisions:
- main.cpp C++ file containing all three FCFS, SSTF, and SCAN algorithms and printed output
- Makefile to compile program
- README file to instruct use of program

Description of any extra features/algorithms/functionality you included which were not required:
- There were no additional features implemented besides handling errors when necessary (e.g. checking for sequence length and ensuring it must be positive).

Description of all known deficiencies or bugs:
- Initially there were issues of the SSTF and SCAN algorithms producing the same total distance even for a randomly generated sequence
- However, it was recognized that the starting cylinder must be a value greater than 0 otherwise both algorithms may scan the sequence from smallest to largest majority of the time.

Lessons Learned:
- The differences between different Disk Arm Scheduling algorithms and how FCFS, SSTF, and SCAN each service disk requests differently given those strategies affect the total disk arm movement.
- Learned to verify algorithm correctness by testing with different starting cylinder positions and random request sequences, and to use compiler warnings and output comparisons to identify logic errors.

